Suppose that $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ are functions which satisfy $f(g(x)) = x^2$ and $g(f(x)) = x^3$ for all $x \ge 1.$  If $g(16) = 16,$ then compute $[g(4)]^3.$
inference:
Setting $x = 16,$ we get
\[f(g(16)) = 16^2 = 256.\]Since $g(16) = 16,$ $f(16) = 256.$  Then
\[g(f(4)) = 4^3 = 64.\]Since $f(4) = 256,$ $g(256) = 64.$

Setting $x = 4$ in $f(g(x)) = x^2,$ we get
\[f(g(4)) = 4^2 = 16.\]Since $f(g(4)) = 16,$ $g(4)$ is a solution to $f(x) = 16.$  But we know $f(16) = 256,$ so $g(4) \neq 16.$  Therefore, $g(4)$ must be a solution to $f(x) = 16$ other than 16.

Setting $x = 256$ in $g(f(x)) = x^3,$ we get
\[g(f(256)) = 256^3.\]Since $f(256) = 16,$ $g(16) = 256^3.$  But $g(16) = 16,$ so $256^3 = 16.$  This means $f(x) = 16$ has the solution $x = 256.$  Therefore, $g(4) = 256,$ so $[g(4)]^3 = 256^3 = \boxed{16}.$
